      Is the SEC unconstitutional?
   =20
 =20

Tomorrow the US Supreme Court will hear arguments in a case about whether t=
he US Securities and Exchange Commission can fine people without a jury tri=
al. The SEC can bring =E2=80=9Cadministrative proceedings=E2=80=9D in its o=
wn in-house courts, in front of SEC employees called administrative law jud=
ges, rather than bringing them in regular courts. A lot of people think tha=
t this is unfair, and in the political and legal climate of 2023, arguments=
 like =E2=80=9Cthis administrative agency has too much power to regulate=E2=
=80=9D go a lot further than they used to.
And so a guy named George Jarkesy allegedly did some quite garden-variety f=
raud with   boiler-room   operator Thomas Belesis, and the SEC  brought an =
administrative case against him a decade ago, and he fought the case by arg=
uing that the SEC should have to sue him in real court, and last year he wo=
n that argument in a federal appeals court in Texas. We   talked about it a=
t the time. And now the SEC has taken it to the Supreme Court.
Jarkesy won in the appeals court=C2=A0on three separate arguments. One was =
that he should have a right to a jury trial. I wrote last year:
I think I agree? At Bloomberg Opinion back in 2015,=C2=A0Noah Feldman wrote=
=C2=A0a good column about this case, saying that it was =E2=80=9Cworth noti=
ng, and mourning, this impending incremental erosion of the constitutional =
protections of a civil trial and the jury right that goes hand in hand with=
 it.=E2=80=9D The SEC has always had the power to bring fraud cases in fede=
ral court, and has a pretty good record there. But in 2010, Congress gave t=
he SEC the power to pursue monetary penalties in its own courts if it wante=
d to. This always seems to=C2=A0cause=C2=A0more=C2=A0trouble=C2=A0than it s=
aves, and is apparently unconstitutional, and I am not sure the SEC will mi=
ss it all that much.
It is not my impression that federal juries are=C2=A0especially=C2=A0sympat=
hetic to fraudsters. Obviously the SEC thinks its odds of winning in front =
of its own judges are better than its odds in front of a jury, and obviousl=
y Jarkesy agrees, and I=E2=80=99m sure they=E2=80=99re right, but I still l=
ike the SEC=E2=80=99s odds in real court. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Greg Stohr   =
writes today:

Backed by Elon Musk and Mark Cuban, Jarkesy contends that defendants in SEC=
 cases have a constitutional right to make their case to a federal jury. A =
win for Jarkesy would reduce the SEC=E2=80=99s leverage to extract expensiv=
e settlements.
=E2=80=9CThe effect for defendants would be significant,=E2=80=9D said Nico=
las Morgan, a lawyer with Paul Hastings and former SEC litigator who filed =
a friend-of-the-court brief for Musk, Cuban and three other business leader=
s who have clashed with the commission. =E2=80=9CPotentially, you would see=
 fewer defendants settle if they know they=E2=80=99re going to be able to p=
lead their case to a jury.=E2=80=9D

Some of that is that people who have a good case won=E2=80=99t settle.=C2=
=A0Cuban, for instance,=C2=A0 did=C2=A0win a jury trial against the SEC. Th=
e SEC charged him with insider trading, alleging that he agreed to a =E2=80=
=9Cwall-cross=E2=80=9D on a public company=E2=80=99s deal and then sold the=
 stock, but a jury was not convinced; an in-house SEC judge might have been=
 more inclined to rule for the SEC.=C2=A0And Musk  settled fraud charges wi=
th the SEC and then immediately regretted it; later he won a jury trial=C2=
=A0in a private lawsuit=C2=A0over the same basic facts. They had real cases=
 to argue to a jury, and it=E2=80=99s only fair that they should have gotte=
n jury trials. And they did! Cuban won at trial; Musk settled, but the SEC=
=E2=80=99s lawsuit against him was filed in real court and demanded a jury =
trial.
Meanwhile I suppose=C2=A0some number of obvious fraudsters will think =E2=
=80=9Cooh I can con a jury too=E2=80=9D and take their chances; I just don=
=E2=80=99t think they=E2=80=99ll do that well.=C2=A0Making the SEC go to re=
al courts in all of its cases seems inconvenient for the SEC but (1) fair a=
nd (2) not=C2=A0that=C2=A0likely to cause an explosion of unpunished fraud.
Another argument that won for Jarkesy in the appeals court was that the way=
 that the SEC appoints administrative law judges is unconstitutional. This =
sort of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0the claim that the statutory methods of appoin=
ting or removing officers of administrative agencies conflict with the US C=
onstitution=E2=80=99s Appointment Clause =E2=80=94=C2=A0is pretty common in=
 court cases about financial regulation, and unfortunately I am absolutely =
allergic to it. I am sure it is important, I just find it very boring. You =
can  read ScotusBlog about it if you want;=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cthe t=
hird question in the case=E2=80=9D in that discussion.=C2=A0
A third argument that won for Jarkesy in the appeals court was that Congres=
s unconstitutionally delegated to the SEC the power to decide whether to br=
ing cases in administrative hearings or real courts. The Constitution says =
that =E2=80=9Call legislative Powers herein granted shall be vested in a Co=
ngress of the United States,=E2=80=9D and there is a theory called the =E2=
=80=9Cnondelegation doctrine=E2=80=9D saying that this means that administr=
ative agencies (like the SEC) can=E2=80=99t do anything =E2=80=9Clegislativ=
e.=E2=80=9D That is, they can=E2=80=99t make rules; only Congress can do th=
at. Or, at least, Congress has to =E2=80=9Cmake the policy decisions,=E2=80=
=9D though agencies can =E2=80=9Cfill up the details.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Of course, agencies like the SEC make rules all the time. Virtually all of =
modern US securities law is in the form of SEC rules. And these rules invol=
ve big policy decisions: Consider the SEC=E2=80=99s rules about cracking do=
wn on   activist hedge funds, or its plans to  regulate climate disclosure.=
 Those are not filling up the details; those are legislative.
The nondelegation doctrine has not had a lot of wins in the Supreme Court i=
n the last 90 years, as we   discussed last year.
  [1]
=C2=A0Generations of law students were taught that it was a thing in the ea=
rly 1930s and ended with the New Deal. But it=E2=80=99s back now: There is =
revived interest in it at the Supreme Court, and Jarkesy won a nondelegatio=
n argument in the appeals court.=C2=A0The argument was that the decision to=
 sue in administrative courts rather than regular courts is=C2=A0a legislat=
ive decision that Congress, not the SEC, had to make; Congress unconstituti=
onally delegated the decision to the SEC with no guidance.
This argument struck me as insane at the time =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Csurel=
y deciding what forum to sue in is an executive action, not a legislative o=
ne,=E2=80=9D I wrote =E2=80=94=C2=A0and still does, but I think=C2=A0it is =
also the most important argument here. The other two arguments are fundamen=
tally about the SEC=E2=80=99s in-house courts, and if Jarkesy wins a total =
victory in the Supreme Court, the result will be that the SEC can=E2=80=99t=
 use those in-house courts as much.
  [2]
=C2=A0Fewer settlements, more jury trials, more wins for people accused of =
fraud, but not a fundamental change in what the SEC=C2=A0does.
But if Jarkesy wins a total victory on the nondelegation argument, that=E2=
=80=99s different. That could mean=C2=A0that all of the SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0=
rulemaking=C2=A0(and every other regulatory agency=E2=80=99s rulemaking) is=
 suspect, that every policy decision that the SEC makes is unconstitutional=
. Much of US securities law would need to be thrown out, or perhaps rewritt=
en by Congress if they ever got around to it. Stuff like the SEC=E2=80=99s =
climate rules would be dead forever.
I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s necessarily a likely outcome here. The=
 Supreme Court could rule against Jarkesy, or it could rule for him on the =
jury-trial stuff without bothering with the nondelegation argument, or it c=
ould rule for him on the nondelegation argument in a narrow way, saying tha=
t this particular delegation is not allowed without undercutting all of the=
 SEC=E2=80=99s rules.=C2=A0Or it could rule against him on the nondelegatio=
n argument (saying that this is not a legislative decision, for instance) w=
hile ruling for him on the jury-trial stuff. In some ways that is the easie=
st outcome: The Supreme Court has several=C2=A0justices who would love to r=
evive the nondelegation doctrine, but this is a somewhat silly case to do i=
t in.
But the Supreme Court=C2=A0does=C2=A0have several justices who would love t=
o revive the nondelegation doctrine in a way that really=C2=A0would=C2=A0un=
dermine most of securities regulation, and while this is a silly case to do=
 it in, it is=C2=A0a=C2=A0case to do it in. You never know! Tomorrow could =
be a big day for the SEC.

