   =20
      OpenAI
   =20
 =20

Yesterday   I wrote out a=C2=A0list of reasons that you might have updated =
your valuation of OpenAI over the past two weeks. You might, I argued, have=
 business or governance or regulatory reasons to think that OpenAI is worth=
=C2=A0more=C2=A0than the $86 billion it was worth two weeks ago.=C2=A0Or yo=
u=C2=A0might have business or governance or regulatory reasons to think it =
is worth=C2=A0less. I also suggested that there might be technological, dev=
elopment-of-artificial-general-intelligence=C2=A0reasons it is worth more: =
The boardroom coup that led to Sam Altman=E2=80=99s brief firing seems to h=
ave been precipitated in part by OpenAI=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cpowerful artific=
ial intelligence discovery=E2=80=9D that allowed it to build a model called=
 Q* that =E2=80=9Cwas able to solve math problems that it hadn=E2=80=99t se=
en before.=E2=80=9D I wrote: =E2=80=9CIf you were willing to buy OpenAI sto=
ck at an $86 billion valuation as a bet that it would develop increasingly =
powerful AI models, evidence that it has in fact developed increasingly pow=
erful AI models should cause you to increase your valuation.=E2=80=9D
In a footnote, I wrote that =E2=80=9Cfor symmetry I want an answer like =E2=
=80=98less than $86 billion, for discovery of artificial general intelligen=
ce reasons,=E2=80=99=C2=A0but I have trouble coming up with a good one.=E2=
=80=9D Of course that was meant as a prompt to my readers. I got a few answ=
ers I want to share with you. One possibility, which I got=C2=A0first=C2=A0=
from Sam Tobin-Hochstadt:
[Perhaps] Q* qualifies as =E2=80=9CAGI=E2=80=9D [artificial general intelli=
gence] and OpenAI=E2=80=99s investment documents give the investors (specif=
ically Microsoft) rights only to pre-AGI technology. So from now on OpenAI =
products will be available to everyone, not just investors.
I am not sure about the details, but OpenAI  says that AGI =E2=80=9Cis excl=
uded from IP licenses and other commercial terms with Microsoft, which only=
 apply to pre-AGI technology,=E2=80=9D and anyway its ultimate mission is t=
o build AGI =E2=80=9Cfor the benefit of humanity.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s pos=
sible that the plan is for=C2=A0OpenAI to=C2=A0ruthlessly commercialize cha=
tbots to make money to build AGI, but once it has built AGI it has to give =
it away for the benefit of humanity.=C2=A0So an OpenAI product that moves=
=C2=A0too=C2=A0close to artificial general intelligence might be=C2=A0bad=
=C2=A0for valuation; it cuts down the time you can profit from chatbots.
Or, more generally, several readers argued=C2=A0that if you think that AGI =
will revolutionize economic life, usher in a post-capitalist paradise, ensl=
ave or eradicate=C2=A0humanity, etc., then achieving AGI makes your investm=
ent in OpenAI worth less. =E2=80=9CIt may be difficult to know what role mo=
ney will play in a=C2=A0post-AGI=C2=A0world,=E2=80=9D OpenAI also says. I a=
m not sure that that should be a reason to reduce your valuation of OpenAI =
specifically =E2=80=94=C2=A0like, that=E2=80=99s bad for your shares in Exx=
onMobil or whatever too, or for your holdings of cash for that matter =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but, sure, a possibility.
One more, from another reader:
OpenAI worth < $86B for tech reasons is definitely possible. It can solve a=
 few math word problems and now the researchers think they have AGI? Who ar=
e these rubes?
I mean that=E2=80=99s probably unfair but it=E2=80=99s also funny.

