   =20
      Hector
   =20
 =20

I can never resist  stories like this:

Barclays is exploring a plan to drop thousands of clients at its investment=
 bank as part of a strategic overhaul that is meant to boost profits and cu=
t =C2=A31bn of costs. =E2=80=A6
Barclays was likely to focus on cutting ties with its least profitable inve=
stment banking clients, people close to the situation said.
This could mean ending relationships with more than 2,500 customers out of =
a total of more than 10,000, although the people stressed no final decision=
s had been made. =E2=80=A6
Barclays=E2=80=99 client management system, known internally as =E2=80=9CHe=
ctor=E2=80=9D, ranks customers, with the top 500 or so tiered into diamond,=
 platinum and gold bands that generate the vast majority of profits.
The rest, classed as silver, do not transact with Barclays often enough or =
at a sufficient scale to earn it a good return.=C2=A0

I used to be an investment banker working almost exclusively on the least p=
rofitable clients, or at least that=E2=80=99s how it felt. The story here i=
s that 5% of clients =E2=80=9Cgenerate the vast majority of profits,=E2=80=
=9D but who do you think generates the vast majority of work? Surely the ot=
her 95%. A $1 billion trade never takes 20 times as much work as a $50 mill=
ion trade, for one thing. But also=C2=A0the client who constantly asks for =
more information and new structures is also the client who puts the trade o=
ut to auction and pays you the minimum possible fee, while the client who j=
ust says =E2=80=9Csure do whatever you want=E2=80=9D about the deal is also=
 the client who says that about the fee.
  [3]

Most of investment banking is, by its nature, unprofitable work: Mostly you=
 pitch deals that won=E2=80=99t happen to clients who won=E2=80=99t hire yo=
u, and only occasionally do you do big lucrative deals for generous repeat =
clients. What a dream, for management to say =E2=80=9Cstop doing all the un=
profitable work and just focus on the clients who pay us lots of=C2=A0money=
.=E2=80=9D Of course for me, having none of those clients, that would have =
meant getting fired, but still.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      FutureCoal
   =20
 =20

We  talked a few months ago about a company called GreenSaif Pipelines Bidc=
o, which is Saudi Aramco. I mean, it isn=E2=80=99t really; it=E2=80=99s a s=
pecial purpose vehicle that owns some Saudi Aramco pipeline joint ventures =
and that sold some bonds to finance them. The bonds found their way into an=
 index of environmental, social and governance investments, because technic=
ally they were=C2=A0not bonds issued by an oil or pipeline company (bad ESG=
) but by an investment company (good=C2=A0ESG, or at least neutral). Even t=
hough =E2=80=9CPipelines=E2=80=9D is right in the name. But =E2=80=9CGreen=
=E2=80=9D is in the name first. If you were an extremely careless ESG inves=
tor =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it is arguably rational to be an extremely careless =
ESG investor? =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might look at that name, see the word =E2=
=80=9CGreen,=E2=80=9D stop reading before you got to =E2=80=9CPipelines,=E2=
=80=9D and buy the bonds. I guess.
Anyway  here=E2=80=99s coal:

The World Coal Association has rebranded itself as =E2=80=9CFutureCoal: The=
 Global Alliance for Sustainable Coal,=E2=80=9D Chief Executive Officer Mic=
helle Manook said at a press conference in Delhi.
=E2=80=9CFor too long our global coal value chain has allowed anti-coal sen=
timent to dominate and fragment us,=E2=80=9D Manook said in a statement. Th=
at=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cresulted in a lowering of the global coal IQ,=E2=80=
=9D which the group defines as an understanding of coal=E2=80=99s contribut=
ion to society.

=E2=80=9CLowering of the global coal IQ=E2=80=9D is a magnificent bit of ma=
rketing and I lost several points of (regular) IQ just by reading it. But p=
resumably the point here is that some investors, activists, governments, et=
c., are going to see that name and read =E2=80=9CThe Global Alliance for Su=
stainable=E2=80=9D and figure =E2=80=9Cah well that=E2=80=99s good then=E2=
=80=9D without getting to the word =E2=80=9CCoal.=E2=80=9D I suppose=C2=A0s=
tarting=C2=A0with =E2=80=9CFutureCoal:=E2=80=9D is a mistake? Really they s=
hould put that off as long as possible. Call=C2=A0it =E2=80=9CFutureGreen: =
The Global Alliance for Responsible, Sustainable and Clean Energy Derived F=
rom Natural Resources Such As Our Favorite Resource, One You Might Have Hea=
rd of, It=E2=80=99s a Really Good One, You=E2=80=99re Not Going to Believe =
This, Get Ready, It=E2=80=99s Coal.=E2=80=9D No one=E2=80=99s gonna read th=
at far.

 =20
   =20
      Sauna arbitrage
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about a fat-finger error at a Nordic electric company=
 that led to Finnish power prices being negative one day last week. I wrote=
: =E2=80=9CThose prices seem to be =E2=80=A6 real? Like, to consumers? I th=
ink not literally negative to consumers, but quite cheap.=E2=80=9D Several =
Finnish readers emailed to say, no, the prices really were negative to cons=
umers, even after all fees, and you could make tens of euros by profligatel=
y wasting electricity that day. Each reader also added that they ran their =
saunas to make a profit.

