VmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD19af0d71" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  discussed last year</a>.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Generations of law students were taught that it was a thing in th=
e early 1930s and ended with the New Deal. But it=E2=80=99s back now: There=
 is revived interest in it at the Supreme Court, and Jarkesy won a nondeleg=
ation argument in the appeals court.=C2=A0The argument was that the decisio=
n to sue in administrative courts rather than regular courts is=C2=A0a legi=
slative decision that Congress, not the SEC, had to make; Congress unconsti=
tutionally delegated the decision to the SEC with no guidance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This argument struck me as insane at the time =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Csurely deciding what forum to sue in is an executiv=
e action, not a legislative one,=E2=80=9D I wrote =E2=80=94=C2=A0and still =
does, but I think=C2=A0it is also the most important argument here. The oth=
er two arguments are fundamentally about the SEC=E2=80=99s in-house courts,=
 and if Jarkesy wins a total victory in the Supreme Court, the result will =
be that the SEC can=E2=80=99t use those in-house courts as much.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Fewer settlements, more jury trials, more wins for people accused=
 of fraud, but not a fundamental change in what the SEC=C2=A0<em>does</em>.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if Jarkesy wins a total victory on the non=
delegation argument, that=E2=80=99s different. That could mean=C2=A0that al=
l of the SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>rulemaking=C2=A0</em>(and every other regul=
atory agency=E2=80=99s rulemaking) is suspect, that every policy decision t=
hat the SEC makes is unconstitutional. Much of US securities law would need=
 to be thrown out, or perhaps rewritten by Congress if they ever got around=
 to it. Stuff like the SEC=E2=80=99s climate rules would be dead forever.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s necessari=
ly a likely outcome here. The Supreme Court could rule against Jarkesy, or =
it could rule for him on the jury-trial stuff without bothering with the no=
ndelegation argument, or it could rule for him on the nondelegation argumen=
t in a narrow way, saying that this particular delegation is not allowed wi=
thout undercutting all of the SEC=E2=80=99s rules.=C2=A0Or it could rule ag=
ainst him on the nondelegation argument (saying that this is not a legislat=
ive decision, for instance) while ruling for him on the jury-trial stuff. I=
n some ways that is the easiest outcome: The Supreme Court has several=C2=
=A0justices who would love to revive the nondelegation doctrine, but this i=
s a somewhat silly case to do it in.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the Supreme Court=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>=
have several justices who would love to revive the nondelegation doctrine i=
